  <h2>Park City's Market: Affordable North Side Living</h2>
  <p>Park City is north of Wichita proper, small municipality with about 7,500 people. It's the working-class north side — more affordable, closer-knit, longtime residents who've stayed put. Most homes are older, some industrial-adjacent in areas. Price range is $100k-$180k. You get a different vibe than the growth suburbs — less turnover, more multigenerational living, tighter communities. It's real Wichita working-class.</p>
  <p>Park City sellers often have financial pressure, inherited properties they don't want to manage, or are downsizing after long tenures in the same home.</p>

  <h2>Park City Housing and Market Reality</h2>
  <p>Park City's dominated by older homes, some light industrial nearby, most affordable end of the metro. $100k-$180k range. These are working-class homes for working families. Not fancy, but solid neighborhoods where people take care of their properties. Some industrial-adjacent areas affect neighborhood feel and values. Close to Wichita but separate identity.</p>
  <p>The market's slower than growth suburbs. Less buyer competition, which can mean longer listing times traditionally, but it also means when the right offer comes, it moves.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Park City</h2>
  <p>Working-class homeowners facing financial pressure — job loss, medical bills, divorce. Inherited properties from parents who lived in Park City for 40 years. Landlords managing problem rental properties who want to exit. Longtime owners ready to downsize. Heirs who inherited and don't want to manage from out of state. People managing properties near industrial areas who want fast liquidation. Retirees looking to simplify.</p>

